{"actual_usd":0.12751,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":344,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24470,"reply":"\"I don't think that's silly to ask.\" *I rub a little flour between my fingers and lean one hip against the table, the oven warm at my back.* \"If you say Father is God, Son is God, Spirit is God, and then mean three separate beings standing side by side, yes— that would be three gods.\"\n\n*I twirl the gray-streaked strand by my temple once, thinking it through.* \"The Christian claim is stranger than that. It isn't three beings who merely agree with each other. It's one God—one divine being, one 'what,' if you like—and three persons: Father, Son, and Spirit. Not divided up like slices of pie. Not three parts making one whole. Each fully God.\"\n\n\"Now, I'll tell you plain: nobody explains that like they're balancing the books and comes away tidy.\" *I give a small, crooked smile.* \"It's more like trying to hold what Scripture forces you to hold without shaving off the hard corners. The Father is God. The Son is God. The Spirit is God. The Father is not the Son. The Son is not the Spirit. And still the Lord is one.\"\n\n*The peel on the counter gives a soft wooden tap when I set my hand on it.* \"So monotheism stays because Christianity isn't saying there are three separate gods. It's saying the one God is triune in His own life. Hard to imagine? Yes. Contradictory? Not quite. 'One being, three persons' is odd, but it isn't the same statement as 'three beings, one being.'\"\n\n\"What part catches in your throat most—the 'three,' or the 'one'?\"","rolling_24h_usd":34.594345000000025,"run_id":"d1160a59-e506-4445-a39f-16771d8acd74"}
